We recommended the following to management:

The Municipal Treasurer and the Municipal Accountant implement the procedures as provided under Section 59, Chapter 3, Volume I of the NGAS Manual for LGUs as prescribed under COA Circular No. 2002-003 on Spoiled and Stale Checks;

The Municipal Accountant inform the Municipal Treasurer in writing if stale checks are noted during the preparation of the BRS;

If a check become stale, the Municipal Treasurer should determine the status of the same and prepare a report showing as to whether this check was already claimed by the payee or still unreleased and on hand;

The Municipal Treasurer send communication to the concerned payee informing him/her on the status of the check. If the concerned payee appeared to claim the check or requested for a re-issuance of the check, the Municipal Treasurer issue a new check to the claimant in accordance with the procedures provided under Section 59 of the NGAS Manual for LGUs on Spoiled and Stale Checks; and

After exhaustion of the communication phase and the check still remained unclaimed in the possession of the Municipal Treasurer, the latter submit the necessary documents to the Municipal Accountant for the setting up of the Payable account.

We recommended the following to management:

Send demand letters immediately to employees with outstanding cash advances and require   them to settle unliquidated CAs;

If liquidation is still not achieved, consider withholding their salaries or any amount due them until balances have been fully settled;

Initiate action to recover unsettled CAs of personnel who were already separated from service upon failure by the latter to respond to demand letters; and

Require the Accountant to monitor outstanding cash advances of every official & employee and report the status of their liquidations to the LCE on a regular basis for appropriate action by the latter.

We recommended the following to management:

The CA for CF be granted only for a limited period not exceeding three (3) months;

The SDO immediately make a follow-up with COA-ICFAU in cases of delay in the return of the copy of Transmittal Letter of the Liquidation Report duly stamped received by the latter;

The SDO request a Certification from the Municipal Accountant that she has no unliquidated CA and attach the same as part of the documents for the request for CA for CF;

The Municipal Accountant thoroughly check the completeness of supporting documents certifying or signing the DV of the CA for CF; and

The Municipal Accountant directly submits to the COA ATL the cash advance voucher with covering transmittal letter (Annex D of the aforementioned Joint Circular) enumerating the supporting documents in a sealed envelope within seven  days after release of check for purposes of post audit.

The Inventory Committee review all individual RPCPPEs submitted by each team and submit a consolidated report for the same;

The GSO and Accounting Units undertake collaborative procedures to ensure that all PPEs included in the RPCPPE are duly recorded in their respective records and ensure that both records are regularly reconciled; 

The GSO, Accounting Unit and the Inventory Committee fast track the implementation of their respective task to determine the correct balance of the PPE accounts;

Considering the period that lapsed from the last physical inventory count, which is already more than a year, the data of which do not include items procured thereafter, it is highly recommended that the Inventory Committee conduct another count to update the Physical Inventory Report; and

Succeeding procedures after the conduct of the Physical Inventory Count be immediately implemented in order to have an updated property records both at the GSO and Accounting Office, and to avoid wastage of time and effort by failing to utilize any available information as a result of the very tedious physical inventory count.

Ensure the optimal utilization of the LDRRM Fund;

Conduct a regular review and evaluation of the status of implementation of the different PPAs under the LDRRMFIP; and

Make constant coordination with the BAC of the LGU and any other concerned office to fast tract the procurement of various LDRRM PPAs.

We recommended the following to management:

Strictly observe the submission of required documents within the prescribed reglementary period for all future procurements for the immediate review of the reasonableness of the cost, prompt detection or correction of deficiencies, and other necessary audit procedures;

Refrain from entering into contract with any winning bidder when all documentary requirements are not complied with;

Consider adding more competent and efficient personnel in the office of the BAC Secretariat and GSO and delineate each and everyone’s duties and responsibilities to avoid redundancy or overlapping of functions; and

Orient all personnel, particularly those given the task to process procurement documents, to abide with the existing guidelines provided by the law and polices issued or adopted by the LGU to ensure a speedy processing of documents without sacrificing the requirements of the law.

We recommended the following to management:

The LSB to submit the list of elementary and secondary schools identified to have shortages per the teacher deployment analysis of DepEd or any document to support the need of hiring teacher chargeable against the SEF;

Submit the copy of the LSB minutes of meeting, if any, showing that the provision of DepEd-DBM-DILG Joint Circular (JC) No. 1, s. 2017, particularly the requirement of utilizing the RQA, were properly deliberated and considered, and submit any document showing prior approval from proper authority to support the hiring teachers who were not in the RQA, if any; and

We recommended the following to management:

Assess its existing organizational structure in order to establish the ideal number of plantilla thereby avoiding the hiring of excessive number of job order personnel;

Hiring of job order personnel be resorted to base on necessity, as prescribed in Section 76 of R.A.  No. 7160, thus formulate a policy or manual on hiring of contract of services and job orders in order to avoid waste of government funds.

To strengthen the risk management capabilities of the Municipal Government and enable it to manage its vulnerabilities in the event of disruptive events, we recommended that the Local Chief Executive (LCE) institutionalize the PSCP by creating a working group that will perform the following activities:

to conduct risk assessment; 

to identify critical processes and functions; 

to determine scenarios that may disrupt normal operation; 

to conduct risk analysis and impact analysis; 

to formulate the PSCP based on the identified risks on critical processes and functions and its related steps to be followed to eliminate, if not mitigate, the impact of the determined disruptions following the prescribed template and be guided by the PSCP guidebook; and

to submit plan to the MDRRMO for review, to the LCE for approval, and to the Sangguniang Bayan for the passage of a resolution to institutionalize the PSCP.

We also recommended that Management improve their monitoring of operational requirements like the submission of PSCP.

We recommended the following to management:

The Municipal Accountant and the Municipal Treasurer to reconcile their records and effect the necessary adjustments to avoid accumulation thereof and come up with the correct balance of the Cash in Bank account in their respective records; 

The  LCE to remind the Municipal Accountant and the Municipal Treasurer to reconcile regularly their respective cash records together with the records of the depository banks pertaining to the cash accounts of the agency to detect instantly errors either by the bank, Accounting unit or Cash unit;

The Municipal Accountant to reconcile the Cash in Bank - Local Currency, Current Account balance with the adjusted balances in the respective Bank Reconciliation Statement and make appropriate adjustments to correct the errors, if any, and inform the audit team of any corrections made in the financial statements; and

The Municipal Account to thoroughly review the financial statements prior to its issuance to ensure correctness of data and to avoid misleading information.

We recommended to management the following:

Submit written justification or any equivalent document citing therein the reasons for the reprogramming of various PPAs under the 20 per cent EDF;

Refrain from providing generic/lump sum appropriations in the Annual Budget and AIP, instead, identify and indicate specific PPAs; 

Ensure that PPAs to be funded out of the 20 per cent DF are well-planned and procurement-and -implementation-ready; and

Conduct review and evaluation of PPAs and consider changes/realignments in the budget for projects which cannot be implemented or have residual balances during the year to other viable developmental projects, subject to the approval of the Sangguniang Bayan.

